<subSubSection id="C36C36BB28574B03FF35FE0CFA9BE565" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" type="materials_examined">
<paragraph id="8BC9653028574B03FF35FE0CFDBCE6CC" blockId="30.[151,619,474,496]" box="[151,619,474,496]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
<typeStatus id="54CDDB9228574B03FF35FE0CFF1EE6CC" box="[151,201,475,496]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Type</typeStatus>
species, 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FE87FE0CFEB2E6CC" box="[293,357,475,496]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="zurqui" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FE87FE0CFEB2E6CC" box="[293,357,475,496]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">zurqui</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A231045928574B03FEC9FE0CFE6BE6CC" box="[363,444,475,496]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
, here designated.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8BC9653028574B03FF35FDCAFA9BE565" blockId="30.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
This new genus is introduced to absorb an unusual diallactiine from 
<collectingCountry id="F36125A028574B03FC08FDC9FBFFE50A" box="[938,1064,541,566]" name="Costa Rica" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Costa Rica</collectingCountry>
, which has the 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FB7EFDCAFA94E50A" box="[1244,1347,541,566]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Haplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FB7EFDCAFA94E50A" box="[1244,1347,541,566]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Haplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<typeStatus id="54CDDB9228574B03FAEEFDC9FAABE50A" box="[1356,1404,542,566]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">type</typeStatus>
of wing venation (
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FEE4FD96FE7AE566" box="[326,429,577,602]" captionStart="FIGURE 15 A – E" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1760,1782]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,495,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[150,1436,483,1738]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 15 A – E. Loboplusia zurqui, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (holotype). C: Scutum, showing prescutellar window, dorsal (paratype). D: Wing (holotype). E: Apex of third tarsomere of midleg with fringed setae, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, E, 0.05 mm, for C, 0.1 mm, for D, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267037/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FED8FD96FE41E566" box="[378,406,577,602]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="15.0">15</number>
D
</figureCitation>
), but is otherwise completely different from other 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FC40FD96FBB4E566" box="[994,1123,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FB7DFD96FA91E566" box="[1247,1350,577,602]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Haplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FB7DFD96FA91E566" box="[1247,1350,577,602]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Haplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36C36BB28574B03FF65FDB2FD88E40D" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8BC9653028574B03FF65FDB2FD88E40D" blockId="30.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FF65FDB2FE96E542" bold="true" box="[199,321,613,638]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FEE8FDB2FE1FE542" box="[330,456,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FEE8FDB2FE1FE542" box="[330,456,613,638]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is the only genus of Winnertziinae, including 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FC7FFDB2FB89E542" box="[989,1118,613,638]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="tribe" tribe="Diallactiini">Diallactiini</taxonomicName>
, whose scutum has a bright membranous window anterior of the scutellum (= prescutellar window, ↓, 
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FC43FD5EFB90E59E" box="[993,1095,649,674]" captionStart="FIGURE 15 A – E" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1760,1782]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,495,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[150,1436,483,1738]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 15 A – E. Loboplusia zurqui, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (holotype). C: Scutum, showing prescutellar window, dorsal (paratype). D: Wing (holotype). E: Apex of third tarsomere of midleg with fringed setae, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, E, 0.05 mm, for C, 0.1 mm, for D, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267037/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FBB7FD5EFBE5E59E" box="[1045,1074,649,674]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="15.0">15</number>
C
</figureCitation>
). Setae on the legs, especially the tarsi, are fringed (
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FE37FD7AFE2AE5FA" box="[405,509,685,710]" captionStart="FIGURE 15 A – E" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1760,1782]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,495,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[150,1436,483,1738]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 15 A – E. Loboplusia zurqui, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (holotype). C: Scutum, showing prescutellar window, dorsal (paratype). D: Wing (holotype). E: Apex of third tarsomere of midleg with fringed setae, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, E, 0.05 mm, for C, 0.1 mm, for D, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267037/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FE6FFD7AFE3EE5FA" box="[461,489,685,710]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="15.0">15</number>
E
</figureCitation>
), a condition I have not noticed in any other mycophagous cecidomyiids. Male genitalia are remarkable for the gonostylus consisting of two lobes (↓, 
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FC6BFD06FBE5E5D6" box="[969,1074,721,746]" captionStart="FIGURE 15 A – E" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1760,1782]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,495,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[150,1436,483,1738]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 15 A – E. Loboplusia zurqui, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (holotype). C: Scutum, showing prescutellar window, dorsal (paratype). D: Wing (holotype). E: Apex of third tarsomere of midleg with fringed setae, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, E, 0.05 mm, for C, 0.1 mm, for D, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267037/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FC5DFD06FBCCE5D6" box="[1023,1051,721,746]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="15.0">15</number>
A
</figureCitation>
), and for the gonocoxae whose ventrobasal bridge is extremely short (↓, 
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FDC1FD22FD1CE432" box="[611,715,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 15 A – E" captionStartId="31.[151,250,1760,1782]" captionTargetBox="[161,1425,495,1727]" captionTargetId="figure@31.[150,1436,483,1738]" captionTargetPageId="31" captionText="FIGURE 15 A – E. Loboplusia zurqui, male. A: Genitalia, ventral (holotype). B: Fourth flagellomere, lateral (holotype). C: Scutum, showing prescutellar window, dorsal (paratype). D: Wing (holotype). E: Apex of third tarsomere of midleg with fringed setae, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, E, 0.05 mm, for C, 0.1 mm, for D, 1.0 mm." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267037/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FD35FD22FD64E432" box="[663,691,757,782]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="15.0">15</number>
A
</figureCitation>
). The ovipositor of 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FC0AFD22FBF1E432" box="[936,1062,757,782]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FC0AFD22FBF1E432" box="[936,1062,757,782]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is more compact (
<figureCitation id="134D79B528574B03FB55FD22FA8BE432" box="[1271,1372,757,782]" captionStart="FIGURE 16 A – D" captionStartId="32.[151,250,1267,1289]" captionTargetBox="[159,1425,199,1240]" captionTargetId="figure@32.[151,1435,193,1246]" captionTargetPageId="32" captionText="FIGURE 16 A – D. Loboplusia zurqui. A: Outline of ovipositor, lateral (paratype). B: Outline of female head, lateral (paratype). C: Female fourth flagellomere, lateral (paratype). D: Outline of male head, lateral (paratype). Scales for A – B, D, 0.1 mm, for C, 0.05 mm. Bc = basicercus, dc = disticercus, gen set = (area of) genal setae, gx = gonocoxa, sg = segment, lbl = labella." httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/267038/files/figure.png" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
Fig. 
<number id="3DBE771728574B03FA89FD22FA91E432" box="[1323,1350,757,782]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" value="16.0">16</number>
A
</figureCitation>
) than that of any other diallactiine I have seen.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C36C36BB28574B03FF65FCEAFDD6E4A2" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8BC9653028574B03FF65FCEAFDD6E4A2" blockId="30.[151,1437,541,926]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FF65FCEAFE99E46A" bold="true" box="[199,334,829,854]" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Etymology.</emphasis>
The generic name is composed of 
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FD71FCEAFCDAE46A" box="[723,781,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Lobo</emphasis>
-, from the Latin word 
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FBAEFCEAFB9EE46A" box="[1036,1097,829,854]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">lobus</emphasis>
for lobe, with reference to the bilobed gonostyli, and the ending - 
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FD83FCB6FDB2E446" box="[545,613,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">plusia</emphasis>
, from 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FD11FCB6FCCDE446" box="[691,794,865,890]" class="Insecta" family="Cecidomyiidae" genus="Haplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FD11FCB6FCCDE446" box="[691,794,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Haplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, a genus with which 
<taxonomicName id="4C761EB328574B03FBA9FCB6FB5EE446" box="[1035,1161,865,890]" class="Insecta" family="Noctuidae" genus="Loboplusia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Lepidoptera" pageId="30" pageNumber="231" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B902B92228574B03FBA9FCB6FB5EE446" box="[1035,1161,865,890]" italics="true" pageId="30" pageNumber="231">Loboplusia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
shares similar venation. Gender of the name is feminine.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
